Quick run through

Load package and example airway data

library( DESeq2 )
library( airway )
data( airway )

The airway data set is taken from Himes et al., RNA-Seq Transcriptome Profiling Identifies CRISPLD2 as a Glucocorticoid Responsive Gene that Modulates Cytokine Function in Airway Smooth Muscle Cells., PLoS One, 2014, 13:e99625. Himes et al. used four cell lines derived from airway smooth muscles cells to study transcriptome changes caused by dexamethasone, an immunosuppressive glucocorticoid drug used for bronchospasms (besides other indications).

library( stringr )
sampleTable <-
   tibble( colname  = colnames( countsTable ) ) %>%
   mutate( assay = str_extract( colname, "(ribo_profile|totalRNA)" ) ) %>%
   mutate( condition = str_extract( colname, "(bmal1_kd|wt)" ) ) %>%
   mutate( time = str_extract( colname, "CT.." ) ) %>%
   mutate( rep = str_extract( colname, "rep." ) ) %>%
   mutate( sample = str_c( condition, "_", rep ) )
sampleTable

Make factors and integers

sampleTable$assay %<>% factor %>% relevel( "totalRNA" )
# This is the same as: 
#    sampleTable$assay <- relevel( factor( sampleTable$assay ), "totalRNA" )
sampleTable$condition %<>% factor %>% relevel( "wt" )
sampleTable$time %<>% factor
sampleTable$sample %<>% factor
sampleTable$hours <- str_replace( sampleTable$time, "CT", "" ) %>% as.integer
sampleTable

We put this together into a DESeq data object

library( DESeq2 )

HOw does this look with logarithmic axes?

ggplot( df ) +
   geom_point(aes( 
      x = log2( libA ),

   coord_fixed()

Turn by 45 degrees (MA plot)

ggplot( df ) +
   geom_point(aes( 
      x = ( log2(libA) + log2(libB) )/2, 
      y = log2(libB) - log2(libA) ) )

Make points semi-transparent, add horizaontal line at 0

ggplot( df ) +
   geom_point(
      aes( 
         x = ( log2(libA) + log2(libB) )/2, 
         y = log2(libB) - log2(libA) ),
      alpha = .1 ) +
   geom_hline( yintercept = 0, col="lightblue" )

Show histogram of log ratioos (log fold changes):

ggplot( df ) +

Paired comparison

Often, samples are paired. To have example of such a case, lets consider this subset of our data, comtaining two sample pairs:

ddsP <- dds[ , dds$assay == "totalRNA" & dds$condition == "wt" & dds$time %in% c( "CT00", "CT10" ) ]

ddsP$sample <- factor( paste( ddsP$condition, ddsP$rep, sep="_" ) )
ddsP$time <- droplevels( ddsP$time )

colData(ddsP)

Each pair is one sample, with one aliquot taken at 0 h and another at 10 h incubation. We want to see which genes change during the incubation.

A simple approach is this:

design( ddsP ) <- ~ time 

ddsP <- DESeq( ddsP )

summary( results( ddsP ) )

We gain power by exploiting that the samples are paired:

design( ddsP ) <- ~ sample + time 

ddsP <- DESeq( ddsP )

summary( results( ddsP ) )

Note: This is a bad example: We have subset to a mere two samples, and this is too few! The airway example used at the beginning has four library pairs, is a better example of good practice.

To understand how to deal with more complex designs, it is helpful to understand the model matrix (a.k.a. *design matrix) arising from the formula above

model.matrix( ~ sample + time, colData(ddsP) )

Side note: To allow for DEseq2s effect-size shrinkage, the design matrix actually used looks somewhat different:

attr( ddsP, "modelMatrix" )

Switching off effect-size shrinkage recovers the standard matrix

ddsP <- DESeq( ddsP, betaPrior=FALSE )
attr( ddsP, "modelMatrix" )

Limma/Voom

Two other popular tools for differential expression analysis of RNA-Seq data are edgeR (McCarthy et al., 2012, Nucl Acid Res 40:4288) and Voom (Law et al, 2014, Genome Res 15:R29), both from G. Smyths group in Melbourne. Here, I repeat the previous analysis with voom:

Limma has not deemed anything significant. Note, however, that this is a not a good example due to the small sample number.

Repeated measures

There are two kinds of time series: (a) A number of independent samples are incubated for different times, and (b) one sample is incubated for the full time, and libraries are prepared from aliquots taken at each time step. In the latter case, these libraries will be correlated simply due to stemming from the same sample. Standard GLMs (as performed by DESeq and edgeR) fail to account for this, and may produce very over-optimistic p values. Limma offers a function, duplicateCorrelation, to estimate the strength for this correlation and then account for it.

For a full analysis of the data, we should hence use limma/voom. For independent-samples time series, DESeq ca ne used, and the user manual contains a chapter on this topic.

Time-series analysis, RNA only

This section merely runs quickly through a limma/voom analysis of the full set of totalRNA samples, to find cycling genes, i.e., genes whose expression follows the circadian rhythm.
